Executive Summary ¶

Online sports betting is becoming legalized and more ubiquitous in many states. Unlike many other forms of betting (ex. poker, blackjack, roulette, craps, etc.), sports betting isn’t predicated on pre-defined and well known probabilities/odds. The inspiration for this project is to assess if through the use of machine learning there are any interesting findings that could lead to successful betting strategies for NFL game betting. We will attempt to accomplish this by leveraging the "NFL Scores and Betting Data" data set on Kaggle found here, https://www.kaggle.com/tobycrabtree/nfl-scores-and-betting-data. To give this a real world goal and metric to compare against we'll also perform a comparison on expected returns our models could have versus major stock indices like the S&P 500, Dow Jones, and NASDAQ to give a sense of opportunity cost.

To try to answer these questions, we first used clustering in order to see if there were any interesting groups in the data. As it turned out, most of the data clustered in one big blob, leading to poor clustering results. This poor result somewhat indicated that we would see less than stellar results from our next task, which was applying supervised learning techniques. The supervised learning methods we attempted were k-nearest neighbors, decision trees, and logistic regression. From all three of those methods, we saw rather poor performance, which the classifiers being roughly the same as random chance. We did see some elevated performance from predicting specific cases, such as looking at only the predictions for bets of the over-under being over. Though, the overall poor performance does not instill a lot of confidence in using these models widely.

While in the scope of our project, we found poor results, there are further avenues to explore that could lead to more fruitful results. One of the major additions would be to add more variables, specific variables relating to team performance, to the dataset. We saw in our analysis that the four variables that related to team performance were in important to many models. Other learning techniques could be tried, such as SVM or even ensemble techniques that leverage multiple models.

Data Cleaning and Transformation ¶

The first major task of this project was to preprocess the data in order to get it into a more useable state. The original dataset included 12627 observations and 22 variables. The main reason for preprocessing is that there is a fair amount of missing data and irrelevant features. The second major task was variable transformation. A major part of that task to add the labels to the data. The first label is if the spread was beat by the favored team, meaning that the favored team had a margin of victory greater than the spread, which the spread in this set is represented by spread favorite. Another major part of the transformation task is to scale the numerical features, as there are a wide range of values in this data set. If they were left unscaled, then the larger value variables could dominate the models. Finally, the categorical variables will be converted into dummy variables. The first part of this task, the removal of some irrelevant features and observations, is detailed below.

Inital Variable & Irrelevant Observation Removal ¶

One of the largest chunks of missing data comes from the fact that the sports betting site that was used to generate the betting features (team favorite id, spread favorite, and over under line) only had data dating back to the 1978 season. So, all seasons prior to that need to be removed due to that lack of sports betting information. Another section of data that needs to be processed are games in which there are no favorite. These rows need to be removed as they make it difficult to generate the label for the spread as betting on the spread just becomes picking the winning team. Most of the irrelevant features relate to the season schedule (schedule data and schedule week) and are not useful features for machine learning. Below goes through the individual steps to accomplish this part of the task.

First, we'll remove schedule_date and schedule_week. They were removed due as they do not make sense to use a predictors.

In [ ]:

Next, we'll remove data from seasons before 1979 as they do not include betting data that is vital to our analysis.

We'll also remove the rows were there is no favorite, as it changes a bet on the spread to just picking a winner, which makes it impossible to add a label for if betting on the spread was a winning spread. Due to its difficulty in labeling and it being a small portion of the data, we felt it was best to just remove those rows

Dealing With Missing Values ¶

This next part of cleaning and process will be on handling other missing values in the data. Most of the other missing values relate to the weather data. There are also some missing values for the over under line. To deal with the weather data, specifically the temperature and wind speed, the rows with the missing data will be removed. While it could be possible to source all of the missing weather data, it would be rather difficult and time consuming due each missing value being a different date and location. We also chose to remove the observations with the missing over-under line as there was only 61 observations with it missing. The data set is large enough that removing the values still leaves us with over 9000 observations. Weather humidity also had quite a few missing values. We chose to replace the missing values with zero as there was over 3000 missing values, which was too large of a portion of data. We also chose to replace it with zero as over 2000 of the observations with missing values were games that were played in domes, meaning there was likely zero humidity. Finally, the last variable with missing values was weather detail, though they were not truly missing as an NA in that row just indicated no special weather detail occurred on the day. Converting that variable into dummy variables got rid of the last of the missing values. Below is a more detailed look at how the missing values were delt with.

We'll now check to see if there is missing data in our dataset.

Transformations ¶

In this section, the labels for the data will be generated. The first label is whether the favored team beat the spread, or their margin of victory was greater than the number set by the sportsbook. To create that label, the home and away names needed to be converted to the team id as the favored team is an id. After that conversion, the label could be generated with checking if the home or away team is the favored team and then seeing if the difference in their score and the underdog’s score is greater than spread value. The second label, whether the over was bet, was simpler as it was just if the total points in the game was greater than the over-under line. There is a third outcome for both of these labels, a push, which occurs when there is no winner because the team either won by exactly the spread amount or the total points equaled the over-under line. We examined how many observations were pushes, which there was only a little over 100 each, and decided to remove those observations. That decision was made as the focus of this analysis to build to models to help find differences between winning and losing bets. A detailed look at this label generation is below.

First, we'll start with generating our first label for beating the over-under. The first step to calculate the total points in each game.

In [ ]:
dataReduced['pointTotal'] = np.sum(dataReduced.iloc[:, 3:5],axis=1).tolist()

Now we'll generate the label which we will name overBeat. 1 will be for when the total points in the game is greater than the over-under line. 0 is for when the total points in the game is less than the over-under line. -1 represents a push or when the total number of points is exactly the over-under line.

In [ ]:
dataReduced.loc[dataReduced['pointTotal'] > dataReduced['over_under_line'], 'overBeat'] = 1
dataReduced.loc[dataReduced['pointTotal'] < dataReduced['over_under_line'], 'overBeat'] = 0
dataReduced.loc[dataReduced['pointTotal'] == dataReduced['over_under_line'], 'overBeat'] = -1

Now we'll generate the label and name it spreadWin. To do that we'll first tackle if the home team is the favored team. If the difference between the home score and away score is greater than the spread, then that represents a covering of the spread, which will be represented by 1. 0 will represent if the home score minus the away score is not greater than the spread and -1 will represent when the home score minus the away score is exactly the spread. That -1 case indicates a push where no one wins.

In [ ]:
dataReduced.loc[(dataReduced['team_home'] == dataReduced['team_favorite_id']) &

dataReduced.loc[(dataReduced['team_home'] == dataReduced['team_favorite_id']) & 
                (dataReduced['score_home'] - dataReduced['score_away'] < abs(dataReduced['spread_favorite'])), 'spreadWin'] = 0
dataReduced.loc[(dataReduced['team_home'] == dataReduced['team_favorite_id']) & 
                (dataReduced['score_home'] - dataReduced['score_away'] == abs(dataReduced['spread_favorite'])), 'spreadWin'] = -1

We'll then do the same as above for if the away team is favored.

Scaling ¶

We'll save a copy of our dataframe just in case an unscaled version of the data is needed.

In [ ]:
dataReducedpred = dataReduced.copy()

Since the data has data of differing size, we will scale the data. If the data went unscaled, then variables with larger variables would dominate the models. So, min max scaling was applied to the data so all numerical features are between 1 and 0.

In [ ]:
minMaxScaler = preprocessing.MinMaxScaler()
dataReduced.iloc[:, np.r_[1:3, 5:11]] = minMaxScaler.fit_transform(dataReduced.iloc[:, np.r_[1:3, 5:11]])

Finally, we will sepearte the target varaibles into their own dataframe.

Below is a kMeans implementation reused from our Machine Learning in Action (MLA) text book. Because the MLA version has the ability to use cosine and euclid distances and its random centroid starting point outputs different cluster results it provides more diversity in clusters we can compare and contrast results between itself and the sklearn's implementation.

In [ ]:
'''
k Means Clustering for Ch10 of Machine Learning in Action
@author: Peter Harrington
'''
from numpy import *

def distEuclid(vecA, vecB):
    return sqrt(sum(power(vecA - vecB, 2))) #la.norm(vecA-vecB)

# Helper function that calculates cosine distance
def distCosine(vecA, vecB):
    # Take 1 minus cosine similarity to convert cosine similarity to a cosine distance
    return (1 - (np.dot(vecA, vecB) / (np.linalg.norm(vecA) * np.linalg.norm(vecB))))

'''
randCent(), creates a set of k ran-dom  centroids  for  a  given  dataset.  
The  random  centroids  need  to  be  within  thebounds of the dataset. 
This is accomplished by finding the minimum and maximumvalues of each dimension 
in the dataset. 
Random values from 0 to 1.0 are then chosenand  scaled  by  the  range  and  
minimum  value  to  ensure  that  the  random  points  arewithin  the  bounds  
of  the  data.  
'''
def randCent(dataSet, k):
	n = shape(dataSet)[1]
	centroids = zeros((k,n), dtype=float)
	for j in range(n): #create random cluster centers
		minJ = min(dataSet[:,j])
		rangeJ = float(max(dataSet[:,j]) - minJ)
		centroids[:,j] = minJ + rangeJ * random.rand(k)
	return centroids 

# kMeans function
def kMeans(dataSet, k, distMeas=distCosine, createCent=randCent):
    m = shape(dataSet)[0]
    clusterAssment = zeros((m,2)) #create mat to assign data points 
                                  #to a centroid, also holds SE of each point
    centroids = createCent(dataSet, k)
    clusterChanged = True
    while clusterChanged:
        clusterChanged = False
        for i in range(m): #for each data point assign it to the closest centroid
            minDist = inf; minIndex = -1
            for j in range(k):
                distJI = distMeas(centroids[j,:],dataSet[i,:])
                if distJI < minDist:
                    minDist = distJI; minIndex = j
            if clusterAssment[i,0] != minIndex: clusterChanged = True
            clusterAssment[i,:] = minIndex,minDist**2
        # print centroids
        for cent in range(k):#recalculate centroids
            ptsInClust = dataSet[nonzero(clusterAssment[:,0]==cent)[0]] #get all the point in this cluster - Note: this was incorrect in the original distribution.
            if(len(ptsInClust)!=0):
                centroids[cent,:] = mean(ptsInClust, axis=0) #assign centroid to mean - Note condition was added 10/28/2013
    return centroids, clusterAssment

In this section we define a helper function to perform kMeans evaluation for varying kMeans model parameters. The function below will take in the

  • data set of NFL objects
  • target set of NFL labels for both spread winners and over/under winners
  • range of k values to evaluate against
  • number of clustering runs/executions to perform for each k
  • kmeans implementation type to use (default is sklearn)

The function will execute clustering for each k value in range multiplied by the number of runs. After complete a report will be generated for each k value displaying a 2D scatter plot visualization of each cluster plot for k using PCA to reduce dimensionality to 2 dimensions. Additionally a summary table will be generated for the completeness and homogeneity scores for both the spreadWin and overBeat labels.

In [ ]:
def kmeans_clustering(data, target, k_range, runs, kmeans_type='sklearn'):
  # Convert data into numpy array
  dataArr = np.array(data)

  for k in k_range:
    print("===============================================================================")
    print("Running kmeans for k =", k)
    print("===============================================================================")
    
    # Initialize lists to store kMeans metrics
    spreadWin_completeness = []
    spreadWin_homogeneity = []
    overBeat_completeness = []
    overBeat_homogeneity = []

    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))
    subplot_loc = 331

    for i in range(runs):
      # Use scikit learn's kmeans implementation to split the data into k clusters
      if (kmeans_type == 'sklearn'):
        kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=123)
        kmeans.fit(dataArr)
        clusters = kmeans.predict(dataArr)
      elif (kmeans_type == 'mla_euclid'):
        centroids, clusters = kMeans(dataArr, k, distEuclid)
        clusters = clusters[:,0]
      elif (kmeans_type == 'mla_cosine'):
        centroids, clusters = kMeans(dataArr, k, distCosine)
        clusters = clusters[:,0]

      # Gather both cluster and target data for spreadWin label
      c = np.array(clusters.astype(int))
      t = np.array(target['spreadWin'].astype(int)).flatten()

      # Calculate spreadWin completeness and homogeneity scores and store
      spreadWin_completeness.append(completeness_score(t, c))
      spreadWin_homogeneity.append(homogeneity_score(t, c))

      # Gather both cluster and target data for overBeat label
      c = np.array(clusters.astype(int))
      t = np.array(target['overBeat'].astype(int)).flatten()

      # Calculate overBeat completeness and homogeneity scores and store
      overBeat_completeness.append(completeness_score(t, c))
      overBeat_homogeneity.append(homogeneity_score(t, c))

      # Convert data into 2D using PCA for cluster visualization
      pca = PCA(2)
      df = pca.fit_transform(data) 

      # Plot the clusters along axis' of length 3
      ax = fig.add_subplot(subplot_loc)
      subplot_loc += 1
      u_labels = np.unique(clusters)
      for i in u_labels:
          plt.scatter(df[clusters == i , 0] , df[clusters == i , 1] , label = i)
      plt.legend()
      plt.plot()

    # Display the results for this k value starting with showing the 2D visualized cluster plots
    plt.show()
    
    # Gather and print stat table for spreadWin cluster scores
    print("spreadWin Cluster Score Summary:")
    print("\tMean completeness score = " + "%.4f" % np.mean(spreadWin_completeness))
    best_run = np.where(spreadWin_completeness == np.amax(spreadWin_completeness))[0][0]
    print("\tBest completeness score = " + "%.4f" % np.amax(spreadWin_completeness) + ", for run = " + str(best_run))
    print("\tMean homogeneity score = " + "%.4f" % np.mean(spreadWin_homogeneity))
    best_run = np.where(spreadWin_homogeneity == np.amax(spreadWin_homogeneity))[0][0]
    print("\tBest homogeneity score = " + "%.4f" % np.amax(spreadWin_homogeneity) + ", for run = " + str(best_run))

    # Gather and print stat table for overBeat cluster scores
    print("overBeat Cluster Score Summary:")
    print("\tMean completeness score = " + "%.4f" % np.mean(overBeat_completeness))
    best_run = np.where(overBeat_completeness == np.amax(overBeat_completeness))[0][0]
    print("\tBest completeness score = " + "%.4f" % np.amax(overBeat_completeness) + ", for run = " + str(best_run))
    print("\tMean homogeneity score = " + "%.4f" % np.mean(overBeat_homogeneity))
    best_run = np.where(overBeat_homogeneity == np.amax(overBeat_homogeneity))[0][0]
    print("\tBest homogeneity score = " + "%.4f" % np.amax(overBeat_homogeneity) + ", for run = " + str(best_run))

Because of these poor results further silhouette analysis was not peformed on each kMeans execution as there doesn't appear to be interesting information to be retrieved from these clusters.

Supervised Learning ¶

k-Nearest Neighbors ¶

In this section we will build multiple kNN supervised learning models varying and tuning parameters to try to optimize predictive qualities.

This section imports all the necessary Python packages (i.e. libraries) additionally required for executing the Python code in this section of the report for calculations and visualizations.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn import metrics
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score, plot_roc_curve
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

In this section we define a helper function to perform kNN evaluation for varying kNN model parameters. The function below will take in the

  • data set of NFL objects
  • target set of NFL labels for both spread winners and over/under winners
  • range of k values to evaluate against
  • a similarity function to use for kNN (default is Euclidean similarity)
  • p dimension for when Minkowski similarity is chosen (default is 2; i.e. Euclidean)

The function will divide the data into an 80/20 split for training and test respectively. Then it will generate the kNN model for each k value using the training data, predict with the test data, and calculate the overall accuracy along with precision for the label classes. It will do this for both the spread winner label and the over/under winner label. Note that precision for both classes was selected as another metric to analyze as it can be very useful in sports gambling (ex. if a model is very much better at selecting overs than unders we'd want to know when using for betting strategies) Also worth noting here is that the kNN model generation will use distance-based weighting to help break ties as it is expected many k values will be even and with a 2 class label create many opportunity for ties.

At the end the function will generate a summary report of the mean, median, and best accuracy and precisions along with a plot for each for visualization.

In [ ]:
def knn_evaluation(data, target, k_range, similarity_metric='euclidean', p_dim=2):

  # Create train/test split of the data and targets with a 80/20 split.  Also pass in a random state for result repeatability
  data_train, data_test, target_train, target_test = train_test_split(data, target, test_size=0.2, random_state=123)

  # Initialize lists to store kNN results
  spreadWin_scores = []
  spreadWin_class_reports = []
  overBeat_scores = []
  overBeat_class_reports = []

  # Loop through for each k passed into this function
  for k in k_range:
    # Use sklearn's kNN classifier for current k and similarity metric passed in to create a classifier for the spreadWin target.  We also 
    # use weights value of distance to break ties as some k values used are expected to be even.
    knn_sw = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k, weights='distance', metric=similarity_metric, p=p_dim) 
    knn_sw.fit(data_train, target_train['spreadWin'])

    # Predict labels using test data
    knn_pred_sw = knn_sw.predict(data_test)
    
    # Evaluate accurray and classification reports for the spreadWin label and store them
    spreadWin_scores.append(metrics.accuracy_score(target_test['spreadWin'], knn_pred_sw))
    spreadWin_class_reports.append(classification_report(target_test['spreadWin'], knn_pred_sw, output_dict=True))

    # Use sklearn's kNN classifier for current k and similarity metric passed in to create a classifier for the overBeat target.  We also 
    # use weights value of distance to break ties as some k values used are expected to be even.
    knn_ob = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k, weights='distance', metric=similarity_metric, p=p_dim) 
    knn_ob.fit(data_train, target_train['overBeat'])
    
    # Predict labels using test data
    knn_pred_ob = knn_ob.predict(data_test)

    # Evaluate accurray and classification reports for the overBeat label and store them
    overBeat_scores.append(metrics.accuracy_score(target_test['overBeat'], knn_pred_ob))
    overBeat_class_reports.append(classification_report(target_test['overBeat'], knn_pred_ob, output_dict=True))

  # Use accuracy scores attained and plot them for spreadWin and overBeat labels
  plt.plot(k_range, spreadWin_scores, label="spreadWin")
  plt.plot(k_range, overBeat_scores, label="overBeat")
  plt.legend()
  plt.title("kNN Accuracy for " + similarity_metric)
  plt.xlabel("k")
  plt.ylabel("Test Accuracy")
  plt.show()

  # Gather and print stat table for spreadWin accuracy
  print("spreadWin Accuracy Summary:")
  print("\tMean accuracy = " + "%.4f" % np.mean(spreadWin_scores))
  print("\tMedian accuracy = " + "%.4f" % np.median(spreadWin_scores))
  best_k = np.where(spreadWin_scores == np.amax(spreadWin_scores))[0][0] + min(k_range)
  print("\tBest accuracy = " + "%.4f" % np.amax(spreadWin_scores) + ", for k = " + str(best_k))

  # Gather and print stat table for overBeat accuracy
  print("overBeat Accuracy Summary:")
  print("\tMean accuracy = " + "%.4f" % np.mean(overBeat_scores))
  print("\tMedian accuracy = " + "%.4f" % np.median(overBeat_scores))
  best_k = np.where(overBeat_scores == np.amax(overBeat_scores))[0][0] + min(k_range)
  print("\tBest accuracy = " + "%.4f" % np.amax(overBeat_scores) + ", for k = " + str(best_k) + "\n\n")

  # Filter for the precision for both classes of spreadWin label
  spreadWin_precision_0 = []
  spreadWin_precision_1 = []
  for i, cr in enumerate(spreadWin_class_reports):
    spreadWin_precision_0.append(cr['0.0']['precision'])
    spreadWin_precision_1.append(cr['1.0']['precision'])

  # Plot the precision for each class in the spreadWin label
  plt.plot(k_range, spreadWin_precision_0, label="spreadWin underdog")
  plt.plot(k_range, spreadWin_precision_1, label="spreadWin favorite")
  plt.legend()
  plt.title("kNN SpreadWin Precision for " + similarity_metric)
  plt.xlabel("k")
  plt.ylabel("Precision")
  plt.show()

  # Gather and print stat table for spreadWin=0 (underdog) precision
  print("Underdog (spreadWin=0) Precision Summary:")
  print("\tMean precision = " + "%.4f" % np.mean(spreadWin_precision_0))
  print("\tMedian precision = " + "%.4f" % np.median(spreadWin_precision_0))
  best_k = np.where(spreadWin_precision_0 == np.amax(spreadWin_precision_0))[0][0] + min(k_range)
  print("\tBest precision = " + "%.4f" % np.amax(spreadWin_precision_0) + ", for k = " + str(best_k))

  # Gather and print stat table for spreadWin=1 (favorite) precision
  print("Favorite (spreadWin=1) Precision Summary:")
  print("\tMean precision = " + "%.4f" % np.mean(spreadWin_precision_1))
  print("\tMedian precision = " + "%.4f" % np.median(spreadWin_precision_1))
  best_k = np.where(spreadWin_precision_1 == np.amax(spreadWin_precision_1))[0][0] + min(k_range)
  print("\tBest precision = " + "%.4f" % np.amax(spreadWin_precision_1) + ", for k = " + str(best_k) + "\n\n")

  # Filter for the precision for both classes of overBeat label
  overBeat_precision_0 = []
  overBeat_precision_1 = []
  for i, cr in enumerate(overBeat_class_reports):
    overBeat_precision_0.append(cr['0.0']['precision'])
    overBeat_precision_1.append(cr['1.0']['precision'])

  # Plot the precision for each class in the overBeat label
  plt.plot(k_range, overBeat_precision_0, label="overBeat under")
  plt.plot(k_range, overBeat_precision_1, label="overBeat over")
  plt.legend()
  plt.title("kNN overBeat Precision for " + similarity_metric)
  plt.xlabel("k")
  plt.ylabel("Precision")
  plt.show()

  # Gather and print stat table for spreadWin=0 (underdog) precision
  print("Under (overBeat=0) Precision Summary:")
  print("\tMean precision = " + "%.4f" % np.mean(overBeat_precision_0))
  print("\tMedian precision = " + "%.4f" % np.median(overBeat_precision_0))
  best_k = np.where(overBeat_precision_0 == np.amax(overBeat_precision_0))[0][0] + min(k_range)
  print("\tBest precision = " + "%.4f" % np.amax(overBeat_precision_0) + ", for k = " + str(best_k))

  # Gather and print stat table for spreadWin=1 (favorite) precision
  print("Over (overBeat=1) Precision Summary:")
  print("\tMean precision = " + "%.4f" % np.mean(overBeat_precision_1))
  print("\tMedian precision = " + "%.4f" % np.median(overBeat_precision_1))
  best_k = np.where(overBeat_precision_1 == np.amax(overBeat_precision_1))[0][0] + min(k_range)
  print("\tBest precision = " + "%.4f" % np.amax(overBeat_precision_1) + ", for k = " + str(best_k) + "\n\n")

Manhattan kNN evaluation ¶

In this section we will define our k range to be from 3 (i.e. # of classes + 1) to 50. Since we have many objects it was felt we could discover more and hopefully increase accuracies and precisions with larger k values. We will use this range for all runs of the kNN evaluator below.

Next we perform our first evaluation using Manhattan similarity. We will perform a run on both the high dimensional data set (115 dimensions) and the low dimensional data set (19 dimensions). As stated earlier, the high dimensional data set retains the characteristics for the home team, away team, and favorite team categorical variables that were converted into dummy variables.

kNN Accuracy Evaluation¶

Comparing the accuracies between the high dimensional and low dimensional data sets we see that there is a small improvement for all accuracies in the low dimensional data set. Here is a summary:

  • Spread winner mean accuracy better at 52.0% vs 51.87%
  • Spread winner best accuracy better at 53.77% vs 52.99%
  • Over/under winner mean accuracy better at 52.07% vs 50.29%
  • Over/under best accuracy better at 53.1% vs 51.61%

This is good as it shows the extra dimensions are not needed from the high dimensional data set and could be dropped to increase kNN performance.

Also worth noting is the spread winner and over/under winner accuracies for the low dimension data set are about the same, as can be seen in the corresponding plot below.

kNN Spread Winner Precision¶

In this section we evaluate the precision for both classes of the spread winner label. Since the numbers support using the low dimensional data set analysis will be focused on those results. When we compare the precision (true positive rate) for when predicting whether an underdog will beat the spread or the favorite will beat the spread we found predictions for underdogs were significantly better. Here is a summary:

  • Mean precision for underdogs was better than favorites, 54.08% vs 48.91%
  • Best precision for underdogs was better than favorites, 56.36% vs 50.98%
  • Best/peak precision for both was found at k = 4. This is good as it decreases computation needed for model prediction.

kNN Over/Under Winner Precision¶

In this section we evaluate the precision for both classes of the over/under winner label. Since the numbers support using the low dimensional data set analysis will be focused on those results. When we compare the precision (true positive rate) for when predicting whether a score will beat the over or under the over/under value we found predictions for unders were slightly better. Here is a summary:

  • Mean precision for unders was better than overs, 52.71% vs 51.36%
  • Best precision for unders was better than overs, 53.78% vs 52.49%
  • Best/peak precision for unders was found at k = 12 and for overs was found at k = 49. This could be compuationally expensive, especially for overs.

#This function makes sure that there are no NA left
def clean_dataset(df):
    assert isinstance(df, pd.DataFrame), "df needs to be a pd.DataFrame"
    df.dropna(inplace=True)
    indices_to_keep = ~df.isin([np.nan, np.inf, -np.inf]).any(1)
    return df[indices_to_keep].astype(np.float64)

Regression ¶

Now we’ll move into regression for predicting the labels for the data. For this task, we will use Logistic regression, as both of our labels are binary and logistic regression is only able to generate predictions for binary variables. The process for building a model and evaluating it will be the same for each label. First, feature selection will be performed in order to have a more understandable model. Feature selection also allows for the compression between the two models to see which features are most important to each label. Logistic regression also helps with determine feature importance, as the coefficients represents the change in odds that the target variable will be 1, so in the case the likelihood that the over will be beaten and the spread will be covered. First, we'll start with building the model and reducing the number of features.

In [ ]:
def generateTable(model, trainSet, testingSet, trainLabels, testingLabels, labelNames):
    accuracies =[]
    for i in range(len(labelNames)):
        cvScore = model_selection.cross_val_score(model[i], trainSet[i], trainLabels[i], cv = 5)
        trainCv = cvScore.mean()
        cvScore = model_selection.cross_val_score(model[i], testingSet[i], testingLabels[i], cv = 5)
        testCv = cvScore.mean()
        accuracies.append([labelNames[i], trainCv, testCv])
    headings = ["Label", "Training Accuracy", "Testing Accuracy"]
    print(tabulate(accuracies, headers=headings))

We'll now define a function to determine the optimal number of features using the cross validation score.

In [ ]:
def optimalFeatures(train, target, model, K):
    results = {"topPercentile": 0, "percentiles" : dict()}
    topScore = -1
    for i in range(1, 100, 5):
        fs = feature_selection.SelectPercentile(feature_selection.f_regression, percentile = i)
        trainFs = fs.fit_transform(train, target)
        score = model_selection.cross_val_score(model, trainFs, target, cv = K, scoring="neg_mean_absolute_error")
        score = abs(score).mean()
        results["percentiles"][i] = score
        # Or statement for the first value
        if score < topScore or topScore == -1:
            topScore = score.mean()
            results["topPercentile"] = i

    return results["topPercentile"], results["percentiles"]

Evaluation ¶

To evaluate the models built using the selected features, we will look at accuracy, the confusion matrix and the metrics that come from it (precision, recall, etc.) and ROC curve along with measuring the area under the ROC curve. We’ll also evaluated the features in each model and compare them between models for the two labels.

First, we'll define a function that prints a classification report, a plot of the confusion matrix, and the roc curve for the model.

In [ ]:
def genStats(model, testSet, targetTest, label):
    preds = model.predict(testSet)
    print("Classification : ")
    print(metrics.classification_report(targetTest, preds))
    print("Confusion Matrix : ")
    confusionMatrix = metrics.confusion_matrix(targetTest, preds)
    plt.matshow(confusionMatrix)
    plt.colorbar()
    plt.title("Confusion Matrix for the " + label)
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()
    metrics.RocCurveDisplay.from_estimator(model, testSet, targetTest)

First we'll run the reporting method for the over label. Starting the classification report, we can see that classifier has very mixed performance. While it has a strong precision value for the zero case, it has value so small it was rounded to zero for the recall. That indicates that while the classifier does not have a lot of false positives for the zero case, it does have a lot of false negatives. The opposite is true for the one case, as it has a weaker precision value, but a strong recall value. The zero cases’ recall value along with the one case’s precision value indicate this classifier is mostly predicting one. This is further shown by the color map on the confusion matrix. The ROC curve is quite poor, as the area under the curve is only slightly above .5 meaning that the model is only slightly better than random chance. That value is so close to .5 that one could probably say that this model is not really any better than random chance overall. This area under the curve value, along with the predictions mostly being one, indicate that this is a quite poor model that does not help show any insights into betting the over.

Regression Summary ¶

Overall, we can see that both models perform quite poorly when it comes to predicting the betting outcomes. While both models had a promising accuracy, their confusion matrices and ROC curves show a different result. Both models had very poor area under the curves and were basically just as good as random chance. In looking at the variables included in both models, an avenue of improving the models might be to include more team statistics, as the only team statistics in the data set were included in both models. Though, due to the overall poor performance, these models should likely not be used when deciding whether to place a bet or not and most of these variables are likely not that important in determining what would be a winning bet.

Conclusion ¶

Most sportsbooks will offer a -110 American odds on spread and over/under bets for NFL games. -110 odds means one would have to bet \$110 to receive a \$100 payout. This equates to an ~91% payout for each successful bet, but a 100% loss for each unsucessful one. This means to be have a positive return, on average, one would have to be better than ~52.4% in prediction accuracy (i.e. better than a coin flip).

The S&P 500, Dow Jones, and NASDAQ all average about 10% annual returns. An NFL season now consists of 17 regular season games. To make the math easier, we won't include the post season. If our betting strategy was to bet on all regular season games each week and compounded the winnings each week (ex. if we come out 5% ahead in Week 1 we bet everything plus that extra 5% in Week 2) we'd have to have a 0.6% return each week to get to a 10% annual return. This was calculated using compount interest equations and compounding interest 17 times. To achieve 0.6% return the our prediction accuracy would need to be ~52.7%. This was calculated by balancing the following equation (Note: we started with \$110 as our initial investment to make the math simpler given the expected -110 odds)

(Winnings ProbabilityOfWin) - (Losses (1 - ProbabilityOfWin)) = 0.006 * InitialInvestment

Plugging in our values we get:

(\$100 * ProbabilityOfWin) - (\$110 (1 - ProbabilityOfWin)) = 0.006 \$110

(\$210 * ProababilityOfWin) - \$110 = \$0.66

(\$210 * ProbabilityOfWin) = \$110.66

ProbabilityOfWin = 0.527 = 52.7%

In assessing all of our kNN, decision tree, and regression results there were only slight margins higher than 50% accuracy in predictions. This is seen in the previous section summaries for each supervised learner where classification reports, confusion matrices, and ROC curves are displayed. Though some accuracy and precision values appear higher than the requisite 52.7% value, wtih only 16 games per week for 17 weeks there is a low sample size and thus much opportunity for volatility. This is especially true when comparing 17 game days vs the stock market that trades every business day of the week, minus holidays.

That all said, given our current models and findings, it would lead to opportunity cost going in favor of a major stock index for investing.

Opportunities for Enhancement ¶

Given what we learned for this project, it is felt there are more opportunities for enhancement that go beyond the scope of our original proposal.

There was discovery that some of the precision and specificity values were higher than the overall accuracy so they could hold some promise in getting further above 52.7% prediction accuracy for single classes.

We, for the most part, confined ourselves to the original predictors of the data set we used from Kaggle. Exploration could be performed to find better predictors with more covariance our labels.

Increasing our breadth of supervised (ex. SVM) and/or unsupervised learners (ex. DBSCAN, HAC) could perhaps lead to better predictive results.

Lastly leveraging ensemble techniques to combine the predictive accuracies, precisions, and specificities of all of our existing models and new ones could increase predictive results as well.

Any combination of any or all of the above could lead to substantially higher than 52.7% prediction accuracy, and thus greater than 10% annual returns.
